          "preamble": "\\section{MO 478499 --- Is this generalized character always a character?}\n\\label{sec:mo478499}\n\\noindent\\textbf{MathOverflow link:} \\href{https://mathoverflow.net/questions/478499}{https://mathoverflow.net/questions/478499}.\n\n\\subsection*{1) FORMAL RESTATEMENT}\nLet $G$ be a finite group and $p$ a prime.\nDefine a class function $\\Psi\\colon G\\to\\mathbb{Z}$ by:\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item If $p\\mid |g|$ then $\\Psi(g)=0$.\n  \\item If $g$ is a $p'$-element (i.e. $p\\nmid |g|$), then\n  \\[\n    \\Psi(g) := |\\{x\\in C_G(g): x \\text{ has order a power of }p\\}|.\n  \\]\n\\end{itemize}\nIt is known (and assumed) that $\\Psi$ is a generalized character.\n\\textbf{Question.} Must $\\Psi$ be a genuine character (a nonnegative integer combination of irreducible characters)?\n\n\\subsection*{2) QUICK LITERATURE/CONTEXT CHECK}\nThe MO post itself notes:\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item in groups of Lie type in characteristic $p$, $\\Psi$ agrees with the square of the Steinberg character;\n  \\item sufficient conditions involving normal $p$-complements in centralizers;\n  \\item an update (Nov 2025) pointing to a paper by G.~Robinson discussing this in a stronger form.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection*{3) ATTACK PLAN}\n\\textbf{Proof track.}\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item Show $\\langle \\Psi,\\chi\\rangle\\ge 0$ for every irreducible $\\chi$.\n  \\item Use structural reduction: normal $p$-complements, block theory, or groups of Lie type.\n\\end{itemize}\n\\textbf{Disproof track.}\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item Search for smallest group $G$ and prime $p$ where some inner product $\\langle\\Psi,\\chi\\rangle$ is negative.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection*{4) WORK}\n\\textbf{PHASE 1 (tiny sanity).}\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item If $p\\nmid |G|$, then every element is $p'$ and the only $p$-power element is $1$, so $\\Psi\\equiv 1$ is the trivial character.\n  \\item If $G$ is a $p$-group, then $\\Psi(1)=|G|$ and $\\Psi(g)=0$ for $g\\ne 1$, so $\\Psi$ is the regular character.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\medskip\n\\textbf{What remains open here.}\nThe general question ``always a character?'' was not proved or disproved in this writeup.\n\n\\subsection*{5) VERIFICATION}\nThe two extreme cases above are correct and give genuine characters.\n\n\\subsection*{6) FINAL}\n\\textbf{UNRESOLVED}.\n\\begin{itemize}\n  \\item (i) Partial results: verification in the cases $p\\nmid |G|$ and $G$ a $p$-group.\n  \\item (ii) First gap: prove nonnegativity of all character inner products in general (or exhibit a group/prime with a negative one).\n  \\item (iii) Next moves: (1) implement a computational search over small groups using character tables; (2) use Robinson's criteria (centralizer normal $p$-complements); (3) test families like alternating groups and small groups of Lie type outside defining characteristic.\n  \\item (iv) A minimal counterexample (if it exists) would likely be a small non-solvable group with mixed $p$-local structure where $\\Psi$ has oscillating values on $p'$-classes.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n% -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n% -----------------------------------------------------------------------------"
